1
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,670
Cecilia was the first to go.

2
00:02:12,753 --> 00:02:15,171
What are you doing here, honey?

3
00:02:15,255 --> 00:02:18,592
You're not even old enough
to know how bad life gets.

4
00:02:18,675 --> 00:02:22,470
Obviously, Doctor,
you've never been a 13-year-old girl.

5
00:02:57,671 --> 00:03:00,591
Everyone dates
the demise of our neighbourhood...

6
00:03:00,633 --> 00:03:03,260
..from the suicides of the Lisbon girls.

7
00:03:04,303 --> 00:03:08,557
People saw their clairvoyance in
the wiped-out elms, the harsh sunlight...

8
00:03:08,641 --> 00:03:11,977
..and the continuing decline
of our auto industry.

9
00:03:12,436 --> 00:03:16,397
Even then, as teenagers,
we tried to put the pieces together.

10
00:03:16,689 --> 00:03:19,025
We still can't.

11
00:03:19,108 --> 00:03:22,403
Now whenever we run into each other
at lunches or parties...

12
00:03:22,487 --> 00:03:25,740
..we find ourselves going over
the evidence one more time.

13
00:03:25,823 --> 00:03:28,993
All to understand those five girls,...

14
00:03:29,118 --> 00:03:32,914
..who, after all these years,
we can't get out of our minds.

15
00:03:35,124 --> 00:03:37,627
Cecilia, the youngest, was 13.

16
00:03:40,755 --> 00:03:43,466
And Lux was 14.

17
00:03:45,510 --> 00:03:48,136
Bonnie was 15.

18
00:03:48,220 --> 00:03:50,722
Mary was 16.

19
00:03:53,350 --> 00:03:55,852
And Therese was 17.

20
00:03:59,022 --> 00:04:02,943
No one could understand how Mrs Lisbon
and Mr Lisbon, our math teacher,...

21
00:04:03,026 --> 00:04:05,779
..had produced such beautiful creatures.

22
00:04:08,323 --> 00:04:12,327
Paul Baldino claimed to have
found Cecilia on her first attempt.

23
00:04:12,411 --> 00:04:14,580
Hey, I was the one who found her.

24
00:04:15,539 --> 00:04:19,083
I was in the storm sewer under my house.
There's all these tunnels.

25
00:04:19,166 --> 00:04:21,252
You could get into anyone's house.

26
00:04:21,335 --> 00:04:23,421
When Paul said this, we believed him...

27
00:04:23,504 --> 00:04:26,632
..because he was the son
of Sammy "the Shark" Baldino,...

28
00:04:26,716 --> 00:04:29,093
..and we knew about his escape tunnel.

29
00:04:29,218 --> 00:04:33,014
So I went up, thinking I could see
one of those girls taking a shower!

30
00:04:33,097 --> 00:04:34,557
Right!

31
00:04:34,640 --> 00:04:36,434
And I walk in...

32
00:04:36,517 --> 00:04:38,311
..and I see blood everywhere.

33
00:04:38,561 --> 00:04:42,732
So I turned around, went for the stairs
and right back out the tunnel.

34
00:04:43,357 --> 00:04:45,443
I had to tell you guys that story.

35
00:04:45,985 --> 00:04:48,195
I'll see you guys later, all right?

36
00:04:50,947 --> 00:04:55,076
- (woman) I heard there was an accident.
- (woman #2) It was no accident, Joan.

37
00:04:55,160 --> 00:04:57,495
Of course the parents are to blame!

38
00:04:58,038 --> 00:05:00,415
I heard they found the razor in the toilet...

39
00:05:00,498 --> 00:05:04,211
Everyone had an opinion
as to why Cecilia had tried to kill herself.

40
00:05:04,836 --> 00:05:08,423
That girl didn't want to die.
She just wanted out of that house.

41
00:05:08,506 --> 00:05:11,218
She wanted out
of that decorating scheme.

42
00:05:15,096 --> 00:05:18,808
The most popular theory
held Dominic Palazzolo to blame.

43
00:05:19,267 --> 00:05:24,396
Dominic was staying with relatives
until his family got settled in New Mexico.

44
00:05:24,480 --> 00:05:27,733
He was the first in our neighbourhood
to wear sunglasses,...

45
00:05:27,816 --> 00:05:30,653
..and within a week of his arrival
he'd fallen in love.

46
00:05:31,820 --> 00:05:35,783
The object of his desire wasn't Cecilia,
but Diana Porter.

47
00:05:40,955 --> 00:05:42,581
I love her!

48
00:05:42,665 --> 00:05:47,002
When Diana Porter left on vacation
in Switzerland, Dominic denounced God.

49
00:05:48,629 --> 00:05:50,673
To prove the validity of his love...

50
00:05:50,798 --> 00:05:54,300
..he jumped off the roof
of his relatives' house.

51
00:06:16,823 --> 00:06:19,367
Ahem! I'm gonna
show you some images,...

52
00:06:19,993 --> 00:06:22,953
..and, uh... you tell me...

53
00:06:25,038 --> 00:06:27,082
..what they remind you of.

54
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:30,127
OK?

55
00:06:46,852 --> 00:06:48,937
A banana.

56
00:06:54,567 --> 00:06:56,611
A swamp.

57
00:07:05,536 --> 00:07:07,413
An Afro.

58
00:07:26,097 --> 00:07:29,184
I don't think Cecilia
truly meant to end her life.

59
00:07:30,685 --> 00:07:32,771
Her act was a cry for help.

60
00:07:34,022 --> 00:07:36,107
I know you're very strict,...

61
00:07:36,191 --> 00:07:41,112
..but I think that Cecilia would benefit
by having a social outlet...

62
00:07:41,196 --> 00:07:44,074
..outside of the codification of school,...

63
00:07:45,492 --> 00:07:49,037
..where she could interact
with males her own age.

64
00:07:56,293 --> 00:08:01,423
Peter Sisten had helped Mr Lisbon install
a model of the solar system in his class.

65
00:08:01,507 --> 00:08:04,552
And in return Mr Lisbon
invited him for dinner.

66
00:08:04,635 --> 00:08:07,012
Bless us, O Lord, and these thy gifts,...

67
00:08:07,096 --> 00:08:11,141
..which we are about to receive from thy
bounty, through Christ our Lord. Amen.

68
00:08:11,433 --> 00:08:12,893
Amen.

69
00:08:12,977 --> 00:08:15,688
Lux, please, put your shirt on this instant.

70
00:08:15,771 --> 00:08:17,856
(whispers) Sorry.

71
00:08:21,360 --> 00:08:24,363
- Thank you, dear.
- Can you pass the salt, please?

72
00:08:24,405 --> 00:08:27,282
- Ham?
- Thank you.

73
00:08:27,365 --> 00:08:30,368
- Sweetheart, would you like some peas?
- I hate peas.

74
00:08:30,493 --> 00:08:31,744
Here.

75
00:08:32,495 --> 00:08:35,039
(father) That's a nice-looking ham, dear.

76
00:08:37,250 --> 00:08:40,211
- Well, thank you, honey.
- (girl) Mm, this is good.

77
00:08:40,295 --> 00:08:43,423
So, Peter, are you an aviation enthusiast?

78
00:08:44,007 --> 00:08:48,636
Well, I don't know if I'd call myself
an enthusiast, but I like planes.

79
00:08:50,722 --> 00:08:52,390
Ah.

80
00:08:52,473 --> 00:08:56,185
Uh, Peter, are you on the football squad?

81
00:08:56,728 --> 00:08:59,688
Um, no, I play it,
but I'm not actually on the team.

82
00:08:59,771 --> 00:09:02,065
- Oh, I see.
- (father) Ah, not a team player.

83
00:09:02,149 --> 00:09:03,817
Do you like to wrestle?

84
00:09:05,152 --> 00:09:08,447
- (girls laugh)
- (father) You OK, Peter?

85
00:09:08,530 --> 00:09:13,327
The Brazilian turbot frog was added to
the endangered species list today.

86
00:09:13,827 --> 00:09:16,496
- That's the third animal this year.
- Oh, dear.

87
00:09:16,580 --> 00:09:19,499
The turbot frog?
I don't think I've ever heard of...

88
00:09:19,583 --> 00:09:21,835
Um, excuse me, may I use the rest room?

89
00:09:21,919 --> 00:09:25,088
Oh, of course. The one down here
isn't working very well.

90
00:09:25,172 --> 00:09:28,508
- Go upstairs through Cecilia's room.
- OK. Thanks.

91
00:10:36,490 --> 00:10:38,784
- (knocking)
- Hold... Hold on.

92
00:10:39,660 --> 00:10:42,329
(giggles) I thought you'd died in there.

93
00:10:43,622 --> 00:10:47,001
Are you done hogging the bathroom?
I need something.

94
00:10:54,508 --> 00:10:56,385
Do you mind?

95
00:10:59,305 --> 00:11:00,764
(giggles)

96
00:11:04,475 --> 00:11:07,937
- Thank you very much.
- You forgetting something?

97
00:11:10,648 --> 00:11:14,194
Oh, Peter. Here's a little aerofoil
I thought you might find amusing.

98
00:11:14,319 --> 00:11:16,237
It's a...

99
00:11:16,321 --> 00:11:19,824
..demonstration of
Bernoulli's principle: lift.

100
00:11:22,952 --> 00:11:25,997
From that time on,
the Lisbon house began to change.

101
00:11:29,584 --> 00:11:31,920
Almost every day,...

102
00:11:32,003 --> 00:11:35,005
..and even when
she wasn't keeping an eye on Cecilia,...

103
00:11:35,088 --> 00:11:37,591
..Lux would suntan wearing a swimsuit...

104
00:11:37,674 --> 00:11:43,055
..that caused the knife sharpener to give
her a 15-minute demonstration for free.

105
00:11:46,099 --> 00:11:50,103
Following the doctor's orders,
two weeks after Cecilia returned home...

106
00:11:50,229 --> 00:11:55,192
..Mr Lisbon persuaded his wife to allow
the girls to throw the first and only party...

107
00:11:55,317 --> 00:11:57,194
..of their short lives.

108
00:12:06,160 --> 00:12:08,204
There. Is that OK?

109
00:12:10,081 --> 00:12:12,166
I'm gonna get dressed.

110
00:12:21,175 --> 00:12:23,636
- Welcome!
- Good evening, Mrs Lisbon.

111
00:12:23,678 --> 00:12:25,805
Come on in.

112
00:12:28,474 --> 00:12:30,601
The party's in the basement.

113
00:12:33,604 --> 00:12:37,440
Just go on round to the left,
and then down the stairs.

114
00:12:38,108 --> 00:12:40,527
(mellow middle-of-the-road music)

115
00:12:50,161 --> 00:12:51,997
Hi, I'm Bonaventure.

116
00:12:52,122 --> 00:12:53,123
Hi.

117
00:12:53,206 --> 00:12:55,250
- Hi. Tim.
- Nice to meet you.

118
00:12:57,002 --> 00:12:58,461
Hi.

119
00:13:01,089 --> 00:13:03,300
- Would you like some punch?
- Yeah.

120
00:13:04,342 --> 00:13:05,594
Thanks.

121
00:13:05,677 --> 00:13:07,761
- Hi.
- Hi.

122
00:13:08,429 --> 00:13:10,306
Thanks.

123
00:13:11,015 --> 00:13:13,100
- Hi.
- Thank you.

124
00:13:15,811 --> 00:13:17,646
- Hey.
- Hi.

125
00:13:17,771 --> 00:13:19,648
Do you wanna sit down?

126
00:13:19,690 --> 00:13:22,026
- Yeah.
- Me too.

127
00:13:44,631 --> 00:13:46,507
(nervous laughter)

128
00:14:03,441 --> 00:14:05,485
Um, how did your SATs go?

129
00:14:06,361 --> 00:14:08,071
OK.

130
00:14:08,154 --> 00:14:10,030
Good.

131
00:14:10,739 --> 00:14:13,158
Do you know where you're applying yet?

132
00:14:13,659 --> 00:14:17,246
Well, no, but my parents
are pushing towards Yale...

133
00:14:17,329 --> 00:14:19,414
..cos that's where my dad went.

134
00:14:20,791 --> 00:14:22,918
That's nice.

135
00:14:25,420 --> 00:14:27,881
You have to imagine
what it'd be like when...

136
00:14:28,006 --> 00:14:32,094
..out of the sun would come the Hun
and his Messerschmitt coming down.

137
00:14:32,177 --> 00:14:35,055
And boys, I swear,
two or three years older than you...

138
00:14:35,138 --> 00:14:38,976
..would be in this - the P51 B Mustang.
B for what? For bull's-eye, see?

139
00:14:41,686 --> 00:14:43,354
You've heard of Yale?

140
00:14:43,437 --> 00:14:45,523
Oh, yeah.

141
00:14:46,732 --> 00:14:48,526
This punch is fantastic.

142
00:14:48,609 --> 00:14:51,320
- Can I give you more?
- Sure. What's in it?

143
00:14:52,572 --> 00:14:55,533
Juices. Some cherry, pineapple.

144
00:14:56,450 --> 00:14:59,745
You know, I uh... I love pineapple.

145
00:15:01,497 --> 00:15:03,165
Really?

146
00:15:12,382 --> 00:15:17,304
This baby would come in, and this won
the war for the United Kingdom. You see?

147
00:15:18,054 --> 00:15:20,348
- Excuse me.
- Sure.

148
00:15:21,016 --> 00:15:25,645
And it's this kind of, uh...
this kind of equipment that makes, uh...

149
00:15:25,729 --> 00:15:27,981
..a model work.

150
00:15:29,608 --> 00:15:31,693
Here's Joe.

151
00:15:33,320 --> 00:15:35,405
- Hi, Joe.
- Hi.

152
00:15:38,033 --> 00:15:42,411
- Now, if he needs anything just call me.
- Oh, I'm sure he'll be fine.

153
00:15:43,287 --> 00:15:44,747
Hi.

154
00:15:45,789 --> 00:15:47,708
Hi.

155
00:15:47,791 --> 00:15:51,212
- Joe! Good to see you. How are ya?
- Hey, Joe.

156
00:15:51,295 --> 00:15:54,131
- Glad you came tonight.
- How's it going?

157
00:15:54,215 --> 00:15:56,091
You're just in time.

158
00:15:56,634 --> 00:15:58,093
Good. Hi.

159
00:15:58,177 --> 00:16:01,096
Everyone look! His ears wiggle
if you scratch his chin.

160
00:16:01,180 --> 00:16:02,640
(laughter)

161
00:16:02,723 --> 00:16:04,808
Joe, sing your song.

162
00:16:05,518 --> 00:16:08,187
# Oh, the monkeys have no tails
in Zamboanga

163
00:16:08,812 --> 00:16:13,317
# Oh, the monkeys have no tails
Got bitten off by whales

164
00:16:13,400 --> 00:16:17,695
# Oh, the monkeys have no tails
in Zamboanga

165
00:16:17,779 --> 00:16:20,532
- (cheering)
- Good job, Joe!

166
00:16:21,032 --> 00:16:23,117
(boy) Good job, Joe.

167
00:16:23,201 --> 00:16:25,495
(# The Hollies. "The Air That I Breathe")

168
00:16:25,578 --> 00:16:27,872
Where'd you learn that song?

169
00:16:29,332 --> 00:16:31,417
May I be excused?

170
00:16:31,834 --> 00:16:35,547
If you want to, dear, but this is your party.

171
00:16:38,216 --> 00:16:42,595
Oh, all right, if you want to go upstairs,
go ahead, but we'll just...

172
00:16:42,679 --> 00:16:45,305
We'll just have to have fun without you.

173
00:16:46,098 --> 00:16:48,725
Oh, look. He always chooses heads.

174
00:16:48,809 --> 00:16:50,894
- Joe, what's it gonna be?
- Heads.

175
00:16:50,978 --> 00:16:53,355
Joe, will you try tails?

176
00:16:54,773 --> 00:16:56,400
Heads it is!

177
00:16:56,525 --> 00:16:58,819
I'll show you again. Let's go.

178
00:16:58,902 --> 00:17:00,529
- Heads.
- Tails.

179
00:17:00,654 --> 00:17:01,905
Heads.

180
00:17:01,989 --> 00:17:04,700
- One more time. In the air, Joe.
- Heads.

181
00:17:08,328 --> 00:17:10,789
Heads it is anyway. One more time here.

182
00:17:10,914 --> 00:17:13,208
- OK, call in the air, Joe.
- Heads.

183
00:17:14,585 --> 00:17:16,711
Heads. Not bad.

184
00:17:18,963 --> 00:17:20,840
How you doin'?

185
00:17:20,965 --> 00:17:22,842
Good.

186
00:17:23,551 --> 00:17:26,888
- You picked it up really well.
- It's my favourite song.

187
00:17:27,638 --> 00:17:30,016
You know, you're... very beautiful.

188
00:17:31,893 --> 00:17:33,978
I could paint you sometime.

189
00:17:35,396 --> 00:17:37,315
Thanks.

190
00:17:42,111 --> 00:17:44,322
- So did they sing it to you?
- Yeah.

191
00:17:44,405 --> 00:17:46,449
(voices and laughter)

192
00:17:47,616 --> 00:17:50,285
(Mr Lisbon) Cecilia!

193
00:17:50,368 --> 00:17:52,412
(startled cries)

194
00:17:53,205 --> 00:17:55,332
Cecilia!

195
00:17:56,208 --> 00:17:58,293
(gasps)

196
00:18:11,806 --> 00:18:13,934
Oh, my God...

197
00:18:14,059 --> 00:18:17,145
No! No! No! Don't look. Turn around.

198
00:18:19,021 --> 00:18:21,398
Turn around. Darlings, turn around.

199
00:18:21,482 --> 00:18:24,401
Don't look. Don't... Don't look at this.

200
00:18:25,027 --> 00:18:27,613
Oh, Jesus. Please, God.

201
00:18:28,614 --> 00:18:31,700
(Mrs Lisbon wails and sobs)

202
00:19:49,109 --> 00:19:51,069
OK.

203
00:20:02,830 --> 00:20:05,458
- What did he say?
- He said she was only 13.

204
00:20:07,585 --> 00:20:09,670
(door bell)

205
00:20:19,514 --> 00:20:21,974
Oh, hi, Mary. Are your parents home?

206
00:20:22,058 --> 00:20:24,100
Hi, Father Moody. Come in.

207
00:20:31,733 --> 00:20:33,818
Oh, hello, Father.

208
00:20:35,403 --> 00:20:37,447
Please, sit down.

209
00:20:38,073 --> 00:20:40,242
Thanks.

210
00:20:40,325 --> 00:20:42,410
Come on, Miller, that was inside.

211
00:20:44,412 --> 00:20:46,456
Ah, no. No, thanks.

212
00:20:49,584 --> 00:20:51,461
(gulps)

213
00:20:55,422 --> 00:20:59,218
How about we get the missus down here,
have a little chat?

214
00:20:59,301 --> 00:21:01,428
Afraid she's under the weather.

215
00:21:01,512 --> 00:21:04,348
(clears throat) She's not really...

216
00:21:04,849 --> 00:21:06,892
..seeing anybody.

217
00:21:08,894 --> 00:21:11,146
Well, she'll see her priest.

218
00:21:11,564 --> 00:21:15,985
Ah! This kid's a sucker
for the high inside ones every time.

219
00:21:16,068 --> 00:21:18,112
Every time.

220
00:21:18,654 --> 00:21:20,823
Excuse me.

221
00:21:23,617 --> 00:21:25,702
Father.

222
00:21:30,623 --> 00:21:34,002
Ah! Double play... Father.

223
00:21:35,962 --> 00:21:38,047
Double play.

224
00:22:00,152 --> 00:22:02,279
Mrs Lisbon?

225
00:22:10,037 --> 00:22:11,705
(knocks)

226
00:22:11,788 --> 00:22:14,249
- May I come in?
- (girl) OK.

227
00:22:18,045 --> 00:22:20,130
Hello, girls.

228
00:22:20,756 --> 00:22:22,841
I thought we could talk.

229
00:22:23,759 --> 00:22:25,844
Do you feel like talking?

230
00:22:27,345 --> 00:22:31,390
Well, if you ever want to,
you know where to find me.

231
00:22:41,317 --> 00:22:43,402
Mrs Lisbon, it's Father Moody.

232
00:22:49,534 --> 00:22:51,828
Mrs Lisbon, hello.

233
00:22:55,581 --> 00:23:01,002
I wanted you to know that
I listed Cecilia's death as an accident.

234
00:23:14,891 --> 00:23:19,354
An accident waiting to happen. John said
you couldn't get a policy to cover it.

235
00:23:19,437 --> 00:23:21,690
I know. It's so incredibly dangerous.

236
00:23:21,773 --> 00:23:23,859
Let's give it a try.

237
00:23:26,862 --> 00:23:28,488
Ready?

238
00:23:28,613 --> 00:23:30,489
One, two, three.

239
00:23:34,243 --> 00:23:37,997
(sighs) Oh, God. It's just so sad.
I can't even believe it.

240
00:23:38,080 --> 00:23:40,166
Footings are too deep.

241
00:23:40,791 --> 00:23:42,668
Got that chain in your truck?

242
00:23:47,131 --> 00:23:49,216
(engine starts)

243
00:24:02,187 --> 00:24:04,230
Hit it!

244
00:24:18,912 --> 00:24:23,333
Our collection of souvenirs
of the Lisbon girls, which still exists,...

245
00:24:23,416 --> 00:24:25,752
..started with Cecilia's diary.

246
00:24:25,835 --> 00:24:29,380
Parkie had gotten it from Skip Ortega,
the plumber's assistant,...

247
00:24:29,464 --> 00:24:31,757
..who had found it next to the toilet.

248
00:24:31,882 --> 00:24:34,510
Tim Weiner - "the Brain" - decoded it.

249
00:24:34,593 --> 00:24:36,720
Emotional instability.

250
00:24:36,803 --> 00:24:40,140
Look at the i's.
The dots on 'em, they're everywhere.

251
00:24:42,100 --> 00:24:43,727
Basically,...

252
00:24:43,852 --> 00:24:45,979
..what we have here is a dreamer.

253
00:24:46,063 --> 00:24:48,524
Someone completely
out of touch with reality.

254
00:24:48,607 --> 00:24:52,027
When she jumped,
she probably thought she would fly.

255
00:24:54,696 --> 00:24:58,116
"Monday, February 13th.
Today we had frozen pizza."

256
00:25:02,245 --> 00:25:06,624
"Thursday. Mom made creamed corn for
dinner. It's the worst. It looks like..."

257
00:25:09,252 --> 00:25:12,213
"Mary chipped her front tooth
on the monkey bars."

258
00:25:12,296 --> 00:25:16,092
"She made a big scene and had to
get it capped. It looks normal, I guess."

259
00:25:16,175 --> 00:25:18,261
Here, give me that.

260
00:25:18,886 --> 00:25:21,222
Told you she had a capped tooth.

261
00:25:26,519 --> 00:25:30,273
Elm trees. How many pages
can you write about dying trees?

262
00:25:32,024 --> 00:25:34,109
Here, something about Dominic.

263
00:25:35,861 --> 00:25:39,406
"Palazzolo jumped off the roof
over that rich bitch Porter."

264
00:25:39,489 --> 00:25:41,867
"How stupid can you be?"

265
00:25:44,119 --> 00:25:46,621
"Today we went out on the boat.
It was cold."

266
00:25:46,705 --> 00:25:48,832
"We saw a couple of whales."

267
00:25:48,915 --> 00:25:52,419
"Lux stroked the whale.
I didn't think they'd stink so much."

268
00:25:52,502 --> 00:25:55,213
"It's the kelp in their baleens rotting."

269
00:25:55,338 --> 00:25:57,674
"I hope we can go again sometime."

270
00:25:58,425 --> 00:26:01,344
Let's read that. "Lux lost it over Kevin..."

271
00:26:01,469 --> 00:26:04,347
- Is it Heines?
- "Heines, the garbage man."

272
00:26:04,389 --> 00:26:07,683
(Cecilia) Lux lost it over Kevin Haines,
the garbage man.

273
00:26:07,766 --> 00:26:11,729
She'd wake up at five in the morning
and hang out on the front steps -

274
00:26:11,812 --> 00:26:13,898
..like it wasn't completely obvious.

275
00:26:13,981 --> 00:26:17,026
She wrote his name in marker
on all her underwear.

276
00:26:17,109 --> 00:26:19,570
Mom found them
and bleached out the Kevins.

277
00:26:19,653 --> 00:26:21,989
Lux was crying on her bed all day.

278
00:26:30,789 --> 00:26:33,334
The trees like lungs filling with air.

279
00:26:34,210 --> 00:26:37,420
My sister, the mean one, pulling my hair.

280
00:26:42,759 --> 00:26:46,638
(narrator) And so we started
to learn about their lives,...

281
00:26:46,721 --> 00:26:50,892
..coming to hold collective memories
of times we hadn't experienced.

282
00:26:50,975 --> 00:26:56,564
We felt the imprisonment of being a girl,
the way it made your mind dreamy...

283
00:26:56,648 --> 00:26:59,317
..so you ended up knowing
what colours went together.

284
00:26:59,400 --> 00:27:02,445
We knew the girls
were really women in disguise,...

285
00:27:02,570 --> 00:27:05,490
..that they understood love
and even death,...

286
00:27:06,407 --> 00:27:11,370
..and that our job was merely to create
the noise that seemed to fascinate them.

287
00:27:11,870 --> 00:27:14,665
We knew that they knew
everything about us.

288
00:27:15,249 --> 00:27:17,334
And that we couldn't fathom them at all.

289
00:27:30,681 --> 00:27:33,725
Hi. Uh, Mrs Lisbon, I'm Lydia Perl.

290
00:27:33,809 --> 00:27:36,103
I'm putting together a... Oh.

291
00:27:36,770 --> 00:27:40,690
- Hi, I'm Bonnie. This is Mary.
- Hello, girls.

292
00:27:40,773 --> 00:27:45,987
Um, I'm here to ask you
a couple of questions about Cecilia.

293
00:27:47,822 --> 00:27:49,282
Yeah?

294
00:27:49,699 --> 00:27:55,454
Great, great. Um, maybe you could start
by telling me a little bit about her.

295
00:27:56,289 --> 00:28:00,126
Did she have any
special interests or hobbies?

296
00:28:00,626 --> 00:28:04,714
- Um, she liked writing in her journal a lot.
- That is great.

297
00:28:05,381 --> 00:28:08,551
Um, OK. Uh, did she...

298
00:28:08,634 --> 00:28:11,344
Did she ever talk about ending her life?

299
00:28:11,803 --> 00:28:13,930
