(men whoop)

744
01:09:10,933 --> 01:09:14,479
This was the time we began to see Lux
making love on the roof...

745
01:09:14,562 --> 01:09:16,397
..with random boys and men.

746
01:09:16,481 --> 01:09:18,983
- Is she naked?
- You can't tell. Hold on.

747
01:09:19,067 --> 01:09:21,152
Well, get it focused.

748
01:09:21,986 --> 01:09:25,615
- Will you stop? Wait your turn.
- What are they doing?

749
01:09:26,282 --> 01:09:29,952
- They're rolling around up there.
- Let me see. Let me see.

750
01:09:30,036 --> 01:09:34,123
Hold on. And she's on him and
he's rubbing his hands through her hair.

751
01:09:34,207 --> 01:09:38,043
- Come on, let me look.
- No, it's my... It's my telescope, Chase!

752
01:09:38,168 --> 01:09:40,962
- (laughs)
- Yes, and what else?

753
01:09:41,046 --> 01:09:45,884
Our male up there
seems to be in a Burger Chalet uniform!

754
01:09:47,928 --> 01:09:52,224
That Burger Chalet - you never think
those guys ever get lucky.

755
01:09:52,474 --> 01:09:55,852
She turns to me and asks me
if I thought what we'd done was dirty.

756
01:09:55,936 --> 01:09:58,230
I knew what to say. I said no.

757
01:09:58,313 --> 01:10:01,316
Then she grabs my hand
and goes "You like me, don't you?"

758
01:10:01,400 --> 01:10:05,237
I didn't say anything.
It's best to keep chicks guessing.

759
01:10:05,320 --> 01:10:09,532
(woman) Chase, honey!
Come practise your violin before dinner!

760
01:10:12,076 --> 01:10:16,247
You're not gonna believe it.
Lux is on the roof again tonight!

761
01:10:16,330 --> 01:10:19,458
- Her hands are moving down.
- I gotta see this!

762
01:10:20,084 --> 01:10:23,587
- This is beautiful.
- No, no. She's on top of him.

763
01:10:24,380 --> 01:10:26,465
- What's she doin', man?
- Wait.

764
01:10:27,842 --> 01:10:30,094
Now they're done, he's getting up.

765
01:10:33,055 --> 01:10:34,932
- That's it?
- Popcorn.

766
01:10:35,015 --> 01:10:36,475
That was quick.

767
01:10:44,190 --> 01:10:46,234
(mutters)

768
01:10:50,488 --> 01:10:53,742
Ooh, good morning!
Good morning (mumbles plant name)

769
01:10:54,200 --> 01:10:56,703
Have we photosynthesised
breakfast today?

770
01:11:05,795 --> 01:11:07,672
(mutters)

771
01:11:07,756 --> 01:11:09,799
Hello, Ronald.

772
01:11:10,467 --> 01:11:12,134
Hi, Eric.

773
01:11:12,217 --> 01:11:15,679
Your daughters haven't been at school
for over two weeks.

774
01:11:17,890 --> 01:11:19,933
You checked out back?

775
01:11:24,688 --> 01:11:27,191
(woman) They found a new math teacher.

776
01:11:28,067 --> 01:11:31,195
- Well, he's gonna have to get another job.
- I know.

777
01:11:32,404 --> 01:11:36,158
(sighs) How long can those girls
be cooped up like that?

778
01:11:56,511 --> 01:11:59,472
- Just go away. This is our tree.
- Girls!

779
01:11:59,555 --> 01:12:03,142
Girls, it's a little late. This tree is dead.

780
01:12:03,226 --> 01:12:06,896
- Why not leave it up to nature?
- If we did, there'd be no trees left.

781
01:12:07,397 --> 01:12:09,690
That's what it's gonna be like anyway.

782
01:12:09,774 --> 01:12:13,318
If boats hadn't brought the fungus,
this wouldn't have happened.

783
01:12:13,402 --> 01:12:15,695
OK? Let's go.

784
01:12:17,781 --> 01:12:19,032
No?

785
01:12:19,491 --> 01:12:21,368
All right. That's it.

786
01:12:21,451 --> 01:12:25,664
I have an order to cut down your elm tree,
but your kids won't let us.

787
01:12:25,747 --> 01:12:30,460
- How do you know that tree's sick?
- It had yellow leaves. The tree is dead.

788
01:12:30,544 --> 01:12:33,880
Our daughter said Aritex is
a less aggressive therapy.

789
01:12:33,964 --> 01:12:37,801
It doesn't work. I leave that tree,
they'll all be gone by next year.

790
01:12:37,884 --> 01:12:40,095
Will be anyway, way things are going!

791
01:12:40,178 --> 01:12:42,472
I don't want to call the police.

792
01:12:42,514 --> 01:12:47,601
Our daughters are standing on their own
front lawn. Since when is that a crime?

793
01:12:49,270 --> 01:12:50,938
Right.

794
01:12:51,021 --> 01:12:52,898
(Mr Lisbon) Uh...

795
01:13:02,700 --> 01:13:07,621
Clive, did you see those girls in the
nighties? That's the shot that I want, OK?

796
01:13:07,705 --> 01:13:10,666
Honey, move forward.
I want those girls in the nighties.

797
01:13:10,750 --> 01:13:14,253
Oh, God. OK.
Here, let's just back up a little bit.

798
01:13:16,588 --> 01:13:18,673
There you go. Is that good? OK?

799
01:13:20,341 --> 01:13:23,553
Four sisters of Cecilia Lisbon,
the East Side teenager...

800
01:13:23,636 --> 01:13:27,891
..whose suicide last summer focused
awareness on a national problem,...

801
01:13:27,974 --> 01:13:34,064
..put their own lives in jeopardy by trying
to protect the elm that Cecilia so loved.

802
01:13:34,147 --> 01:13:36,232
(chain saws buzz)

803
01:14:26,364 --> 01:14:29,367
For the next few weeks
we hardly saw the girls at all.

804
01:14:31,786 --> 01:14:35,456
Joe Hill Conley didn't call Therese
as he had promised.

805
01:14:40,461 --> 01:14:42,880
And Lux never spoke to Trip again.

806
01:14:46,300 --> 01:14:48,385
(Trip) You're a stone fox.

807
01:14:53,682 --> 01:14:56,184
The girls' only contact with the outside...

808
01:14:56,268 --> 01:15:00,105
..was through catalogues they ordered
that filled their mailbox...

809
01:15:00,188 --> 01:15:05,861
..with pictures of high-end fashions
and brochures for exotic vacations.

810
01:15:06,611 --> 01:15:08,613
Unable to go anywhere,...

811
01:15:08,697 --> 01:15:12,617
..the girls travelled in their imaginations
to Siamese temples...

812
01:15:12,701 --> 01:15:17,831
..or passed an old man with a leaf broom
tidying a moss-carpeted speck of Japan.

813
01:15:20,124 --> 01:15:22,460
We ordered the same catalogues...

814
01:15:22,543 --> 01:15:26,672
..and, flipping through the pages,
we hiked through passes with the girls,...

815
01:15:26,756 --> 01:15:31,010
..stopping every now and then
to help them with their backpacks,...

816
01:15:31,093 --> 01:15:34,305
..placing our hands
on their warm, moist shoulders...

817
01:15:34,388 --> 01:15:37,266
..and gazing of fat papaya sunsets.

818
01:15:38,893 --> 01:15:41,645
We drank tea with them
in a water pavilion.

819
01:15:42,521 --> 01:15:44,565
We did whatever we wanted.

820
01:15:45,941 --> 01:15:49,862
Cecilia hadn't died.
She was a bride in Calcutta.

821
01:15:53,031 --> 01:15:55,492
The only way
we could feel close to the girls...

822
01:15:55,575 --> 01:16:00,538
..was through these impossible trips
which have scarred us forever,...

823
01:16:00,622 --> 01:16:04,125
..making us happier
with dreams than wives.

824
01:16:06,086 --> 01:16:11,132
Collecting everything we could of theirs,
the Lisbon girls wouldn't leave our minds.

825
01:16:11,216 --> 01:16:13,259
But they were slipping away.

826
01:16:13,676 --> 01:16:18,848
The colour of their eyes was fading, along
with the locations of moles and dimples.

827
01:16:18,932 --> 01:16:21,017
From five they had become four,...

828
01:16:21,101 --> 01:16:25,813
..and they were all living in the dead,
becoming shadows.

829
01:16:25,896 --> 01:16:29,483
We'd have lost them completely
if they hadn't contacted us.

830
01:16:29,566 --> 01:16:31,693
OK, one long,...

831
01:16:32,403 --> 01:16:34,363
..two short...

832
01:16:34,988 --> 01:16:37,116
- ..and one long.
- Mm-hm.

833
01:16:37,199 --> 01:16:38,951
You got that? That's it.

834
01:16:42,371 --> 01:16:44,498
"Help."

835
01:16:44,957 --> 01:16:47,042
"Send...

836
01:16:48,252 --> 01:16:50,170
..bo...

837
01:16:50,254 --> 01:16:51,755
..bo."

838
01:16:53,715 --> 01:16:55,216
- Bo-bo?
- Bo-bo.

839
01:16:55,299 --> 01:16:58,344
That's what it says: bo-bo.

840
01:16:58,428 --> 01:17:02,724
"Help send bo-bo"?
I thought you knew Morse code.

841
01:17:31,168 --> 01:17:33,253
Something here for you.

842
01:17:41,011 --> 01:17:43,096
I got one, too.

843
01:17:45,474 --> 01:17:48,393
We racked our brains
for a way of contacting them.

844
01:17:48,477 --> 01:17:52,647
Tom Faheem suggested we fly a kite
with a message alongside the house,...

845
01:17:52,731 --> 01:17:54,940
..but that had logistical problems.

846
01:17:55,066 --> 01:17:58,361
In the end, the answer was so simple
it took a week to work out.

847
01:17:58,944 --> 01:18:00,988
We called them on the telephone.

848
01:18:01,364 --> 01:18:03,032
727...

849
01:18:03,115 --> 01:18:06,202
- ..8221 .
- 8221 .

850
01:18:06,327 --> 01:18:08,621
(whispers) Get ready.

851
01:18:10,748 --> 01:18:13,209
- (Mary) Hello?
- Go!

852
01:18:15,795 --> 01:18:18,130
(Todd Rundgren) # Hello, it's me

853
01:18:20,800 --> 01:18:25,679
# I've thought about us
for a long, long time

854
01:18:25,805 --> 01:18:27,889
Call us. 727 0487.

855
01:18:33,353 --> 01:18:35,814
- (phone rings)
- Shit! It's them.

856
01:18:41,403 --> 01:18:44,447
(Gilbert O'Sullivan)
# To think that only yesterday

857
01:18:44,531 --> 01:18:46,991
# I was cheerful, bright and gay

858
01:18:47,158 --> 01:18:49,744
# Looking forward to - who wouldn't do? -

859
01:18:49,828 --> 01:18:52,622
# The role I was about to play

860
01:18:52,706 --> 01:18:55,375
# But in my hour of need

861
01:18:55,458 --> 01:18:58,001
# I truly am indeed

862
01:18:58,085 --> 01:19:00,045
# Alone again

863
01:19:00,629 --> 01:19:02,089
# Naturally

864
01:19:02,172 --> 01:19:08,262
(The Bee Gees)
# Run to me whenever you're lonely

865
01:19:08,345 --> 01:19:14,601
# Run to me if you need a shoulder

866
01:19:14,685 --> 01:19:21,275
# Now and then you need someone older

867
01:19:21,358 --> 01:19:23,652
# So darling

868
01:19:23,777 --> 01:19:27,448
(Carole King) # So far away

869
01:19:27,531 --> 01:19:33,786
# Doesn't anybody stay
in one place any more?

870
01:19:34,203 --> 01:19:40,084
# It would be so fine
to see your face at my door

871
01:19:41,210 --> 01:19:48,217
# Doesn't help to know you're just far

872
01:19:48,301 --> 01:19:50,386
# Away

873
01:19:50,470 --> 01:19:52,555
I gotta go home. See ya tomorrow.

874
01:19:53,056 --> 01:19:55,099
I'll see you later.

875
01:19:58,853 --> 01:20:02,189
- (Lux) We're suffocating.
- (Mrs Lisbon) You're safe here.

876
01:20:02,272 --> 01:20:04,149
I can't breathe in here.

877
01:20:05,859 --> 01:20:07,944
No answer.

878
01:20:29,841 --> 01:20:32,343
- (Tim) What time is it?
- (Chase) Any time now.

879
01:20:33,094 --> 01:20:35,388
- Guys, there it is.
- What?

880
01:20:39,350 --> 01:20:41,644
(Tim) Yeah, it's them.

881
01:20:42,561 --> 01:20:44,647
(all) Let's go!

882
01:20:56,117 --> 01:20:58,619
(whispers) I have keys to my mom's car.

883
01:21:06,418 --> 01:21:08,920
- (clatter)
- Shh!

884
01:21:22,726 --> 01:21:24,769
Maybe we should knock.

885
01:21:26,896 --> 01:21:28,189
(knocks)

886
01:21:30,525 --> 01:21:31,776
We're here.

887
01:21:42,202 --> 01:21:44,246
About time.

888
01:21:44,329 --> 01:21:46,415
We've been waiting for you guys.

889
01:21:46,957 --> 01:21:50,377
We got a car, a full tank.
We'll take you anywhere you wanna go.

890
01:21:50,461 --> 01:21:52,838
It's just a Cougar, but it's got a big trunk.

891
01:21:53,338 --> 01:21:55,090
Can I sit up front?

892
01:21:56,633 --> 01:21:58,093
Sure.

893
01:22:00,763 --> 01:22:04,057
Which one of you
is gonna sit up front next to me?

894
01:22:05,433 --> 01:22:07,101
Where are your parents?

895
01:22:08,019 --> 01:22:09,479
Asleep.

896
01:22:09,562 --> 01:22:12,982
- What about your sisters?
- They're coming.

897
01:22:13,816 --> 01:22:16,277
Come on, it's getting late.

898
01:22:17,528 --> 01:22:21,574
Wait five minutes. We had to wait
until my parents were asleep.

899
01:22:21,657 --> 01:22:25,411
They take for ever.
My mom's an insomniac.

900
01:22:29,540 --> 01:22:32,251
We better take our car.
There's more room.

901
01:22:33,920 --> 01:22:36,213
Think you can handle a station wagon?

902
01:22:37,297 --> 01:22:40,342
Sure. It's not a stick, is it?

903
01:22:40,425 --> 01:22:42,928
- No.
- Yeah, no problem.

904
01:22:43,178 --> 01:22:46,515
- Will you let me steer?
- Sure.

905
01:22:46,890 --> 01:22:50,143
But maybe we should go.
I heard somethin'. Could be your mom.

906
01:22:50,894 --> 01:22:52,979
Come on in.

907
01:23:02,989 --> 01:23:07,118
I'll go wait in the car.
You guys wait here for my sisters.

908
01:23:25,219 --> 01:23:27,304
(girls giggling)

909
01:23:32,476 --> 01:23:34,687
(humming)

910
01:23:39,274 --> 01:23:41,192
(thud)

911
01:24:03,256 --> 01:24:07,218
These girls are making me crazy.
If I could feel one of 'em up just once...

912
01:24:10,846 --> 01:24:12,514
What?

913
01:24:16,477 --> 01:24:18,354
(creaking)

914
01:24:18,437 --> 01:24:20,522
(hissing)

915
01:24:29,907 --> 01:24:33,243
We would never be sure
about the sequence of events.

916
01:24:33,744 --> 01:24:35,829
We argue about it still.

917
01:24:38,957 --> 01:24:42,794
Most likely Bonnie had died while we
were waiting in the living room,...

918
01:24:42,877 --> 01:24:44,962
..dreaming of highways.

919
01:24:46,005 --> 01:24:49,175
Mary put her head in the oven
shortly thereafter.

920
01:24:49,926 --> 01:24:54,514
Therese, stuffed with sleeping pills,
was gone by the time we got there.

921
01:24:55,306 --> 01:24:57,141
Lux was the last to go.

922
01:24:57,225 --> 01:24:59,310
(engine running)

923
01:25:00,937 --> 01:25:02,855
(coughs)

924
01:25:06,984 --> 01:25:11,279
It's four o'clock on Sunday afternoon.
Do you know where your children are?

925
01:25:11,363 --> 01:25:14,491
(reporters' voices overlapping)

926
01:25:20,080 --> 01:25:22,124
(babble of voices)

927
01:25:27,129 --> 01:25:30,882
This has been Lydia Perl
with Channel 8 News.

928
01:25:40,100 --> 01:25:43,644
(Mrs Lisbon) None of my daughters
lacked for any love.

929
01:25:45,104 --> 01:25:47,898
There was plenty of love in our house.

930
01:25:49,734 --> 01:25:52,028
I never understood why...

931
01:26:23,975 --> 01:26:29,606
After the suicide free-for-all the Lisbons
gave up any attempt to lead a normal life.

932
01:26:31,941 --> 01:26:34,652
They had Mr Hedlie pack up the house,...

933
01:26:34,736 --> 01:26:37,906
..selling what furniture he could
in a garage sale.

934
01:26:40,241 --> 01:26:42,744
Mr Lisbon put the house on the market...

935
01:26:42,827 --> 01:26:45,746
..and it was sold to
a young couple from Boston.

936
01:26:46,372 --> 01:26:50,376
We, of course, took the family photos
that were put out with the trash.

937
01:26:50,459 --> 01:26:52,086
(clock ticking)

938
01:26:53,420 --> 01:26:58,300
We had pieces of the puzzle, but however
we put them together, gaps remained -

939
01:26:59,009 --> 01:27:02,763
..oddly shaped emptiness,
mapped by what surrounded them...

940
01:27:02,888 --> 01:27:05,224
..like countries we couldn't name.

941
01:27:08,644 --> 01:27:15,274
What lingered after them was not life,
but the most trivial list of mundane facts.

942
01:27:18,444 --> 01:27:20,613
..a clock ticking on the wall,...

943
01:27:21,823 --> 01:27:24,117
..a room dim at noon,...

944
01:27:25,243 --> 01:27:29,831
..the outrageousness of a human being
thinking only of herself.

945
01:27:34,502 --> 01:27:38,256
We began the impossible process
of trying to forget them.

946
01:27:44,929 --> 01:27:48,223
Our parents seemed
better able to do this,...

947
01:27:48,306 --> 01:27:51,560
..returning to their tennis foursomes
and cocktail cruises...

948
01:27:51,643 --> 01:27:54,813
..as though they'd seen this all before.

949
01:27:55,272 --> 01:28:00,610
It was full-fledged summer again, over
a year since Cecilia had slit her wrists,...

950
01:28:00,694 --> 01:28:03,280
..spreading the poison in the air.

951
01:28:03,363 --> 01:28:06,575
A spill at the plant
increased the phosphates in the lake...

952
01:28:06,658 --> 01:28:10,996
..and produced a scum of algae so thick
that the swamp smell filled the air,...

953
01:28:11,079 --> 01:28:13,623
..infiltrating the genteel mansions.

954
01:28:14,624 --> 01:28:18,461
Debutantes cried over the misfortune
of coming out in a season...

955
01:28:18,544 --> 01:28:21,505
..everyone would remember
for its bad smell.

956
01:28:21,589 --> 01:28:25,676
The O'Conners, however,
came up with the ingenious solution...

957
01:28:25,760 --> 01:28:30,014
..of making the theme of their daughter
Alice's debutante party "Asphyxiation".

958
01:28:30,097 --> 01:28:34,060
Like everyone else,
we went to forget about the Lisbon girls.

959
01:28:35,144 --> 01:28:37,438
(woman) She'll give him a heart attack!

960
01:28:44,445 --> 01:28:46,530
(muffled voices)

961
01:29:06,925 --> 01:29:08,968
(muffled voices)

962
01:29:22,523 --> 01:29:24,608
Hi, Parkie.

963
01:29:25,150 --> 01:29:27,027
(vomits)

964
01:29:28,946 --> 01:29:31,407
Al's got the acting bug, you know.

965
01:29:33,075 --> 01:29:35,369
- She caught it from Pinkie.
- (laughter)

966
01:29:36,537 --> 01:29:39,707
And I want to announce tonight
that next fall...

967
01:29:39,832 --> 01:29:43,168
..Alice is going to
a little school in New Haven(!)

968
01:29:44,086 --> 01:29:45,838
(laughter)

969
01:29:45,963 --> 01:29:49,216
I hear they have
a great drama school out there.

970
01:29:49,299 --> 01:29:53,511
- In fact, Sam, didn't your father build it?
- That's the law school.

971
01:29:55,263 --> 01:29:59,017
We're so proud of Alice.
We really couldn't be prouder.

972
01:29:59,392 --> 01:30:01,477
(all toast)

973
01:30:07,108 --> 01:30:09,360
I've had it.

974
01:30:09,444 --> 01:30:11,654
Goodbye, cruel world.

975
01:30:17,744 --> 01:30:20,538
No, no, no, you don't understand me!

976
01:30:20,621 --> 01:30:23,123
I'm a teenager. I got problems!

977
01:30:23,915 --> 01:30:26,001
(laughter)

978
01:30:33,717 --> 01:30:36,636
So much has been said
about the girls over the years.

979
01:30:39,431 --> 01:30:41,933
But we have never found an answer.

980
01:30:44,644 --> 01:30:47,814
It didn't matter in the end
how old they had been,...

981
01:30:49,441 --> 01:30:51,526
..or that they were girls.

982
01:30:53,903 --> 01:30:56,781
